Architecture for Low-Code CPU Sub-Agent System

Based on the deductive synthesis paradigm  and formal verification approaches , here's a proposed architecture:

1. Specification Agent (Constraint Extraction)
- Input: Natural language or formal ISA specification
- Output: Formal logic formulas (pre/postconditions), register maps, instruction encodings
- Method: Uses SMT-LIB or similar formalisms rather than neural generation
- Deterministic guarantee: Specification parsing uses formal grammars, no ambiguity

2. Microarchitecture Agent (Structure Synthesis)
- Input: Formal specification + target constraints (power, area, timing)
- Output: Structural RTL skeleton (pipeline stages, hazard detection, forwarding logic)
- Method: 
  - Sketch-based synthesis  with CEGIS (CounterExample-Guided Inductive Synthesis)
  - Templates for common CPU types (single-cycle, multi-cycle, pipelined, out-of-order)
  - Constraint solving for pipeline depth and hazard resolution
- Deterministic guarantee: Same constraints → same architecture every time

3. Implementation Agent (Code Generation)
- Input: Structural skeleton + ISA formal spec
- Output: Synthesizable Verilog/VHDL (or HLS C++)
- Method:
  - Grammar-based code generation (not neural)
  - Rosette/SMT-backed synthesis 
  - Domain-specific languages (DSL) for CPU components (ALU, register file, control unit)
- Deterministic guarantee: Grammar production rules are deterministic; no randomness

4. Verification Agent (Correctness Proof)
- Input: Generated RTL + ISA specification
- Output: Formal correctness proof or counterexample
- Method:
  - riscv-formal style approach : Automatic generation of checkers from ISA spec
  - Symbolic execution (Rosette/Knox) 
  - Equivalence checking against golden ISA model
- Deterministic guarantee: Mathematical proof, not probabilistic confidence

